<subSubSection id="C3546572FFA5FFB0FF21FA11FEBEC667" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="173" pageId="1" pageNumber="172" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BF136F9FFA5FFB3FF21FA11FC8EC0CD" blockId="1.[136,1452,820,2071]" pageId="1" pageNumber="172">
<emphasis id="B93AEAEBFFA5FFB3FF21FA11FEA4C1EC" bold="true" box="[189,315,1648,1674]" pageId="1" pageNumber="172">Discussion</emphasis>
: 
<emphasis id="B93AEAEBFFA5FFB3FEDFFA10FEC3C1EC" box="[323,348,1649,1674]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="172">—</emphasis>
The architecture of the inflorescence, shape of the leaves and floral morphology of 
<taxonomicName id="4C4E4D7AFFA5FFB3FB7AFA11FA33C1EC" box="[1254,1452,1648,1674]" class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Sarcoglottis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asparagales" pageId="1" pageNumber="172" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="matogrossensis">
<emphasis id="B93AEAEBFFA5FFB3FB7AFA11FA33C1EC" box="[1254,1452,1648,1674]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="172">S. matogrossensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are reminiscent of 
<taxonomicName id="4C4E4D7AFFA5FFB3FEC4FAF5FC0CC1C9" authority="(Romero-Gonzalez et al. 2010: 514)" baseAuthorityName="Romero-Gonzalez" baseAuthorityPageNumber="514" baseAuthorityYear="2010" box="[344,915,1684,1711]" class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Sarcoglottis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asparagales" pageId="1" pageNumber="172" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="maroaensis">
<emphasis id="B93AEAEBFFA5FFB3FEC4FAF5FE6BC1C8" box="[344,500,1684,1710]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="172">S. maroaënsis</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFDF4B08FFA5FFB3FD9EFAF5FC14C1C9" author="Romero-Gonzalez, G. A. &amp; Fernandez-Concha, G. C. &amp; Ormerod, P." box="[514,907,1684,1711]" pageId="1" pageNumber="172" pagination="513 - 519" refId="ref3386" refString="Romero-Gonzalez, G. A., Fernandez-Concha, G. C. &amp; Ormerod, P. (2010) Novelties in the Orchis flora of Venezuela II - Cranichideae. Lankesteriana 9: 513 - 519. https: // doi. org / 10.15517 / lank. v 0 i 0.12112" type="journal article" year="2010">
Romero-González 
<emphasis id="B93AEAEBFFA5FFB3FD44FAF4FC96C1C8" box="[728,777,1684,1710]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="172">et al</emphasis>
. 2010: 514
</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C4E4D7AFFA5FFB3FC02FAF5FBACC1C8" authorityName="Pabst" authorityYear="1969" box="[926,1075,1684,1710]" class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Sarcoglottis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asparagales" pageId="1" pageNumber="172" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="amazonica">
<emphasis id="B93AEAEBFFA5FFB3FC02FAF5FBACC1C8" box="[926,1075,1684,1710]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="172">S. amazonica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C4E4D7AFFA5FFB3FBF5FAF5FB72C1C8" authorityName="Schlechter" authorityYear="1920" baseAuthorityName="Rolfe" baseAuthorityYear="1896" box="[1129,1261,1684,1710]" class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Sarcoglottis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asparagales" pageId="1" pageNumber="172" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="metallica">
<emphasis id="B93AEAEBFFA5FFB3FBF5FAF5FB72C1C8" box="[1129,1261,1684,1710]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="172">S. metallica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. However, it can be distinguished by the light green, discoloured leaves that may or may not be variegated with white spots (
<emphasis id="B93AEAEBFFA5FFB3FAB1FAD8FAD3C1B4" box="[1325,1356,1721,1746]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="172">vs.</emphasis>
reddish, brownish, or chocolate-purplish with irregular, bright green spots on the adaxial surface and homogeneously purplishred on the abaxial surface); the flowering which occurs after the senescence of the leaves (
<emphasis id="B93AEAEBFFA5FFB3FB16FB60FB36C07C" box="[1162,1193,1793,1818]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="172">vs.</emphasis>
fresh leaves present at flowering); and by the petals with apices conspicuously free, acute and reflexed (
<emphasis id="B93AEAEBFFA5FFB3FB96FB44FBB6C058" box="[1034,1065,1829,1854]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="172">vs.</emphasis>
adhering to the dorsal sepal nearly to the apex, obtuse, and straight). From 
<taxonomicName id="4C4E4D7AFFA5FFB3FDDAFB29FD7DC004" box="[582,738,1864,1890]" class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Sarcoglottis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asparagales" pageId="1" pageNumber="172" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="maroaensis">
<emphasis id="B93AEAEBFFA5FFB3FDDAFB29FD7DC004" box="[582,738,1864,1890]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="172">S. maroaënsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
specifically, it can also be distinguished by the glabrous lip (
<emphasis id="B93AEAEBFFA5FFB3FA11FB28FA3BC004" box="[1421,1444,1865,1890]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="172">vs</emphasis>
. rugose thickening near the apex of the apical lobe and extending to the apex of the central portion of the lip) and the apical lobe with an entire margin (
<emphasis id="B93AEAEBFFA5FFB3FD95FBF0FDBFC0CC" box="[521,544,1937,1962]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="172">vs</emphasis>
. crenate and plicate).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF136F9FFA5FFB0FF21FBD5FEBEC667" blockId="1.[136,1452,820,2071]" lastBlockId="2.[136,1451,158,257]" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="173" pageId="1" pageNumber="172">
With the recently described 
<taxonomicName id="4C4E4D7AFFA5FFB3FD95FBD5FCF7C0A8" authority="(Salazar et al. 2019)" baseAuthorityName="Salazar" baseAuthorityYear="2019" box="[521,872,1972,1999]" class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Sarcoglottis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asparagales" pageId="1" pageNumber="172" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="neillii">
<emphasis id="B93AEAEBFFA5FFB3FD95FBD5FDF5C0A8" box="[521,618,1972,1998]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="172">S. neillii</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFDF4B08FFA5FFB3FDE1FBD5FCFFC0A8" author="Salazar, G. A. &amp; Tobar, F. &amp; Jimenez-Machorro, R. &amp; Freire, E. &amp; Penafiel, M." box="[637,864,1972,1999]" pageId="1" pageNumber="172" pagination="1 - 8" refId="ref3633" refString="Salazar, G. A., Tobar, F., Jimenez-Machorro, R., Freire, E. &amp; Penafiel, M. (2019) Sarcoglottis neillii (Orchidaceae: Spiranthinae), a new species from the Andean Tepui Region of Ecuador and Peru. Phytotaxa 427: 1 - 8. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / phytotaxa. 427.1.1" type="journal article" year="2019">
Salazar 
<emphasis id="B93AEAEBFFA5FFB3FD41FBD4FC8DC0A8" box="[733,786,1972,1998]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="172">et al</emphasis>
. 2019
</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C4E4D7AFFA5FFB3FCE4FBD5FBDBC0A8" box="[888,1092,1972,1998]" class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Sarcoglottis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asparagales" pageId="1" pageNumber="172" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="matogrossensis">
<emphasis id="B93AEAEBFFA5FFB3FCE4FBD5FBDBC0A8" box="[888,1092,1972,1998]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="172">S. matogrossensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
shares the floral structure and predominantly green leaves. The latter can be easily distinguished by the narrowly elliptical to oblanceolate leaves (
<emphasis id="B93AEAEBFFA5FFB3FA11FBB8FA3BC094" box="[1421,1444,2009,2034]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="172">vs</emphasis>
. elliptical to ovate) that are proportionally larger (13.6–22.2 
<emphasis id="B93AEAEBFFA5FFB3FC87FB9CFCADCF70" box="[795,818,2045,2070]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="172">vs</emphasis>
. 
<quantity id="4CB69B1CFFA5FFB3FCDCFB9DFC3ECF71" box="[832,929,2044,2071]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.0" metricValueMax="13.0" metricValueMin="5.0" pageId="1" pageNumber="172" unit="cm" value="9.0" valueMax="13.0" valueMin="5.0">5−13 cm</quantity>
long.), by the petals with apices conspicuously free, acute, and reflexed (
<emphasis id="B93AEAEBFFA6FFB0FE30FCFEFE54C7DE" box="[428,459,159,184]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="173">vs.</emphasis>
adherent internally to the dorsal sepal except at their little free recurved apices, obtuse and sometimes obscurely apiculate); and flowering occurs after the senescence of the leaves (
<emphasis id="B93AEAEBFFA6FFB0FB3BFCA2FB59C7BA" box="[1191,1222,195,220]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="173">vs.</emphasis>
fresh leaves present at flowering).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<caption id="DF316671FFA6FFB0FF14FB04FCCDC0A5" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5757559" ID-Zenodo-Dep="5757559" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5757559/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="173" startId="2.[136,229,1893,1915]" targetBox="[215,1377,306,1838]" targetPageId="2">
<paragraph id="8BF136F9FFA6FFB0FF14FB04FCCDC0A5" blockId="2.[136,1452,1893,1987]" pageId="2" pageNumber="173">
